1. Overview

The Nitrologic Foundry Client is a commandâ€‘line research client designed to interact with language models and manage file sharing. Written in JavaScript/TypeScript for execution with Deno, the client leverages several permissions (run, env, net, read, write) and is intended for experimentation with model evaluations, conversation histories, and file submission workflows.

2. Key Features

â€¢ Chat Interface and History Management  
â€ƒâ€“ The client provides an interactive prompt (using raw mode via Denoâ€™s stdin reader) that accepts chat messages and commands.  
â€ƒâ€“ It maintains a conversation history (â€œrohaHistoryâ€) for both user queries and model responses, allowing for conversation snapshots and history restoration via save and load functionality.  
â€ƒâ€“ A â€œrelayâ€ function communicates with model endpoints (using the OpenAI client libraries and several API providers such as GEMINI, DEEPSEEK, XAI, and OpenAI) and appears to support models that have tool call capabilities.

â€¢ File Sharing and Submission  
â€ƒâ€“ The â€œ/shareâ€ command enables users to designate files or directories for sharing. Individual files are processed (for text, JSON, markdown, etc.) or converted to Base64 for binary content.  
â€ƒâ€“ A sharing mechanism tracks file metadata (path, size, modification time, hash) and tags shared files.  
â€ƒâ€“ The client supports a â€œ/pushâ€ or â€œ/commitâ€ command that scans shared files, detects modifications or deletions, andâ€”if changes are detectedâ€”updates the chat history and files submitted for review.

â€¢ Configuration and Customization  
â€ƒâ€“ Several configuration flags allow toggling features such as committing shares on start, ANSI rendering of markdown, slow output, verbose debugging information, and logging (to a file â€œfoundry.logâ€).  
â€ƒâ€“ The â€œ/configâ€ command lists available flags, which include:  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ commitonstartâ€‚ (commit shared files on start)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ toolsâ€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚(enable model tool interface)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ ansiâ€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚(render using ANSI/markdown)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ slowâ€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚(output at reading speed)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ verboseâ€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚(emit debug information)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ brokenâ€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚(ansi background blocks via alternate colors)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ loggingâ€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚â€‚(log all output to file)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ resetcountersâ€‚â€‚(reset counters on reset)  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ returntopushâ€‚â€‚(prompt to â€œpushâ€ when returning)

â€¢ Model Management and Tooling Interface  
â€ƒâ€“ The client supports selecting models via the â€œ/modelâ€ command. The list of available models is gathered from multiple API endpoints (configured in the â€œaccounts.jsonâ€ file) and stored in a list (â€œmodelListâ€).  
â€ƒâ€“ It uses tool call functions if the selected model supports the tools interface. Three tool functions are defined:  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ—‹ read_time â€“ returns current UTC time.  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ—‹ submit_file â€“ submits a file for review by sending content type and file content, saving the file to a â€œforgeâ€ directory.  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ—‹ annotate_foundry â€“ permits setting descriptions on objects like tags or shared files.  
â€ƒâ€“ The â€œrelayâ€ function is responsible for interfacing with the model. It prepares the payload (using either the simple chat history or a tool call JSON structure) and recursively handles tool call responses by executing the corresponding functions (via â€œonCallâ€) before forwarding the results back into the conversation cycle.

3. Architecture and Workflow

â€¢ Initialization and Configuration  
â€ƒâ€“ On startup, the client checks for a â€œfoundry.jsonâ€ state file, creating one with default settings if not present.  
â€ƒâ€“ It reads â€œaccounts.jsonâ€ to establish connections with the configured AI endpoints; these connections use API keys from environment variables.  
â€ƒâ€“ The client also initializes conversation history (rohaHistory) with a system prompt (â€œI am testing foundry client. You are a helpful assistantâ€).

â€¢ File and Directory Operations  
â€ƒâ€“ Commands such as â€œ/cdâ€ and â€œ/dirâ€ allow the user to manage current working directories â€“ aiding in file selection for sharing.  
â€ƒâ€“ The client uses Deno APIs for file operations, including reading, writing, statting files, and computing file hashes using SHAâ€‘256.

â€¢ Command Processing  
â€ƒâ€“ Input lines that begin with a â€œ/â€ are interpreted as commands. Otherwise, they are treated as chat messages from the user.  
â€ƒâ€“ A command â€œcallCommandâ€ function handles a wide range of commands: listing accounts, toggling configuration flags, sharing files, managing tags, and handling model selection.
â€ƒâ€“ Commands such as â€œ/resetâ€ clear shared files and conversation history; â€œ/historyâ€ lists recent conversation activities; â€œ/saveâ€ and â€œ/loadâ€ allow the user to persist or restore sessions.

â€¢ ANSI and Markdown Rendering  
â€ƒâ€“ The client can render markdown content with ANSI escape sequences for styling (headers, bold, italics, bullets).  
â€ƒâ€“ There is a fallback plain output mode if ANSI rendering is not enabled.

â€¢ Isolation and Sandbox Execution  
â€ƒâ€“ A helper function â€œisolateCodeâ€ is provided to run external JavaScript code (from an â€œisolation/test.jsâ€ file) in a sandboxed environment with restricted permissions. This supports a â€œrunCodeâ€ routine that demonstrates isolated execution.

