1. Overview

The Nitrologic Foundry Client is an experimental commandâ€‘line research tool built on Deno. It is designed to facilitate model evaluation, interactive chat sessions, and file sharing. The client interacts with multiple language model endpoints (such as those provided by OpenAI, Deepseek, Gemini, and XAI) and supports both chat and file submission through a unified interface.

2. Key Features

â€¢ Interactive Chat Interface and Conversation History  
â€ƒâ€“ The client runs in a terminal and uses raw input mode to capture user commands and messages.  
â€ƒâ€“ Conversation history is maintained in an array (â€œrohaHistoryâ€), starting with a system prompt that defines the clientâ€™s role.  
â€ƒâ€“ Users may save and reload conversation sessions, allowing for persistent session management.

â€¢ File Sharing and Commit Workflow  
â€ƒâ€“ The â€œ/shareâ€ command allows a user to submit either files or entire directories.  
â€ƒâ€“ Shared files are tracked via metadata including file path, size, modification time, and a computed SHAâ€‘256 hash.  
â€ƒâ€“ A â€œ/pushâ€ (or â€œ/commitâ€) command scans the shared files for modifications or deletions, updates history, and integrates file â€œsubmissionsâ€ into the conversation for review.

â€¢ Configurable Options and Command Set  
â€ƒâ€“ Multiple configuration flags control aspects such as:  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ Automatic file commit on start  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ ANSI-based markdown rendering for enhanced terminal output  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€¢ Slow reading (output pacing), verbose logging, and even special â€œbrokenâ€ modes for ANSI blocks  
â€ƒâ€“ Commands such as â€œ/configâ€ allow users to toggle these features.  
â€ƒâ€“ Additional commands include â€œ/cdâ€ (to change directory), â€œ/dirâ€ (to list files), â€œ/modelâ€ (to select or switch language models), and â€œ/resetâ€ (to clear history and file shares).

â€¢ Model and Tool Functionality  
â€ƒâ€“ The client supports model interactions using a â€œrelayâ€ function that sends the conversation history as a payload to the selected model endpoint.  
â€ƒâ€“ Some models support â€œtool calls,â€ and the client defines three tool functions:  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ—‹ read_time â€“ Returns the current UTC time  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ—‹ submit_file â€“ Accepts content and its MIME type to save a file in the local â€œforgeâ€ directory  
â€ƒâ€ƒâ—‹ annotate_foundry â€“ Lets the user annotate or set descriptions on file shares or tags  
â€ƒâ€“ These tools support enhanced interactions when the underlying model can invoke external functions during a conversation.

â€¢ ANSI and Markdown Rendering  
â€ƒâ€“ The client renders markdown content using ANSI escape sequences (for headers, bold, italics, and bullet lists), improving readability in terminal outputs when enabled.  
â€ƒâ€“ A fallback plain text mode is available if ANSI rendering is turned off.

â€¢ Sandbox Code Execution  
â€ƒâ€“ A dedicated â€œisolationâ€ module demonstrates running external JavaScript code in an isolated environment with limited permissions. This reinforces the clientâ€™s role as a research and testing platform.

3. Architecture and Workflow

â€¢ Initialization and Startup  
â€ƒâ€“ On launch, the client checks for a persistent state file (â€œfoundry.jsonâ€). If not found, it creates a default configuration.  
â€ƒâ€“ It reads an â€œaccounts.jsonâ€ file to load provider configurations and uses environment variables to obtain API keys for connecting to endpoints.

â€¢ Conversation Handling  
â€ƒâ€“ User input is processed in two categories: commands (prefixed with â€œ/â€) and regular chat messages.  
â€ƒâ€“ The â€œcallCommandâ€ function handles a variety of commands (e.g., file management, configuration toggles, model selection) and directs appropriate actions.  
â€ƒâ€“ The â€œrelayâ€ function packages the chat history (or a squashed version of it) and sends it to the AI endpoint using either a simple completion or a tool invocation model, with recursive handling of tool responses as needed.

â€¢ File and Directory Management  
â€ƒâ€“ The client uses Denoâ€™s filesystem API to change directories (â€œ/cdâ€), list directory contents (â€œ/dirâ€), and compute file hash values for file integrity checking.  
â€ƒâ€“ Shared files are maintained in an internal list (roha.sharedFiles) and include optional tags that can be annotated post sharing.

â€¢ Configurability and Logging  
â€ƒâ€“ The client supports multiple configuration options stored within the state file, allowing toggles for behaviors such as automatic commit at startup and slow output pacing.  
â€ƒâ€“ There is also an option to log all output to a â€œfoundry.logâ€ file.

4. Supporting Files and Documentation

â€¢ foundry.md â€“ A markdown document that describes available commands and the machine interface (tool calls) for the client.  
â€¢ welcome.txt â€“ Provides a graphical welcome message on startup.  
â€¢ LICENSE.txt â€“ Contains the MIT License terms under which the source is released.  
â€¢ build.bat â€“ A batch script to compile the application using Denoâ€™s compile command, ensuring necessary permissions are granted.  
â€¢ The â€œforgeâ€ directory â€“ A local repository for submitted files and session snapshots.  
â€¢ The â€œisolationâ€ directory â€“ Contains sandboxed test code that is executed at startup to verify isolated code execution capabilities.

5. Summary and Concluding Remarks

The Nitrologic Foundry Client is a well-structured research tool merging interactive chat, file management, and model tool-call support. Its versatility lies in the ability to manage conversation sessions, track and submit file changes, and toggle between different aspects of its behavior with a simple command interface. The modular designâ€”combining terminal I/O, file system manipulation, and API integration via Denoâ€”makes it a useful platform for model evaluation and interactive research.

Future enhancements might include richer command-line navigation (such as arrow key support and auto-completion), improved error handling around API calls, and greater configurability for advanced users. As it stands, the Foundry Client provides a compelling example of combining AI interactivity with common file management tasks in a terminal-based environment.

